occurrences.line_text: Dye rather, dye, then euer so faire loue forsake.
Dye rather, dye, then euer so faire loue forsake.
But rather chose to dye for sorrow great,
Yet might not do him dye, but aye more fresh
Where in eternall bondage dye he must,
That thousand deathes me leuer were to dye,
To do fowle death to dye, or wrap in grieuous woe.
That he mote algates dye, yet did his death forgiue.
Yet can he neuer dye, but dying liues,
To better boot, but let me dye, that ought;
And Scudamore here dye with sorrowing.
Dye rather, then doe ought, that mote dishonour yield.
And all his armour did with purple dye;
He would with whipping, him haue done to dye:
Ne stayeth leaue to take, before his friends doe dye.
Before I saw faire Pastorella dye.
Meat fit for such a monsters monsterous dyeat.
And cast her colours dyed deepe in graine,
As selfe to dyen bad, vnburied bad to beene.
He daily dyde, yet neuer throughly dyen couth.
Dyes not, when breath the bodie first doth leaue,
Who dyes the vtmost dolour doth abye,
Without regard of good, dyes like ill grounded seeds.
The deare remembrance of his dying Lord,
And sucked vp their dying mothers blood,
That I his shield haue quit from dying foe.
With dying fit, that downe she fell for paine.
Of death, that here lye dying euery stound,
Fled fast away, halfe dead with dying feare:
If not well ended at our dying day.
And trouble dying soules tranquilitee.
Who dying whylome did diuide this fort
He lately heard that dying Lady grone,
To hide his coward head from dying dreed.
And dying daily, daily yet reuiue:
Another did the dying bronds repaire
Who dying left none heire them to withstand,
Three sonnes he dying left, all vnder age;
He dying left the fairest Tanaquill,
Whence spring all noble deeds and neuer dying fame:
Of dying people, during eight yeares space,
Proud of his dying honor and deare bands,
Dye rather, dye, and dying do her serue,
Dying her serue, and liuing her adore;
The which he dying left next in remaine
Yet can he neuer dye, but dying liues,
Dying each day with inward wounds of dolours dart.
Dreadfully dropping from her dying hart,
The cruell steele, which thrild her dying hart,
In which I daily dying am too long.
By all that dying to it turned be?
By all that dying into it doe fade.
Of carcases, which dying on her fell.
And in his armes the dreary dying mayd,
Of those, that hauing saued her from dying,
They trembling stood, and made a long broad dyke,
White hand Eunica, proud Dynamene,
For nought was giuen them to sup or dyne,
Emongst the woodie hilles of Dyneuowre:
Or other dyrefull hap from heauen or hell
Then doth the dï¿½dale earth throw forth to thee
Which wast begot in Dï¿½mogorgons hall,
Y e gentle Ladies, in whose soueraine powre
Sucking vpon her poisonous dugs, each one
And ouerflow each plaine and lowly dale:
His holy things each morne and euentyde:
And for her Dwarfe, that wont to wait each houre;
But euery hill and dale, each wood and plaine
Do backe rebut, and each to other yeeldeth land.
Each others equall puissaunce enuies,
Faire seemely pleasaunce each to other makes,
Both day and night, of each degree and place,
Their gay attire: each others greater pride does spight.
But to Duess' each one himselfe did paine
Do ride each other, vpon her to gaze:
To be aueng'd each on his enimy.
With greedy force each other doth assayle,
And each to deadly shame would driue his foe:
And two were browne, yet each to each vnlich,
And two were browne, yet each to each vnlich,
Each other bent his enimy to quell,
That fainting each, themselues to breathen let,
Who hath endur'd the whole, can beare each part.
Each dore he opened without any breach;
But friendly each did others prayse deuize
And loue establish each to other trew,
Is then vniust to each his due to giue?
Each goodly thing is hardest to begin,
And knew his good to all of each degree,
And greatly ioy each other well to see:
Each bone might through his body well be red,
Through famous Poets verse each where renownd,
And boystrous battell make, each other to auenge.
Proceeded, yet each one felt secretly
Their beuers bright, each other for to greete;
Goodly comportance each to other beare,
Which feedes each liuing plant with liquid sap,
Drew them in parts, and each made others foe;
Accourting each her friend with lauish fest:
And to his mistresse each himselfe stroue to aduaunce.
Each other does enuie with deadly hate,
They wist their houre was spe[n]t; the[n] each to rest him hyes.
They both nigh were, and each bad other flie:
Each trembling leafe, and whistling wind they heare,
Each stroue to please, and others pleasure to fulfill.
And naked made each others manly spalles;
And each one sought his Lady to aggrate:
Themselues to court, and each a Damsell chose:
Themselues did solace each one with his Dame,
And each his portion peaceably enioyd,
But each his paines to others profit still employd.
Whilest each of Brutus boasted to be borne,
Where each might best offend his proper part,
And vnto each a Bulwarke did arret,
That is each thing, by which the eyes may fault:
Yet each doth in him selfe it well perceiue to bee.
Thereof she vsd to giue to drinke to each,
So striuing each th'other to vndermine,
Each did the others worke more beautifie;
And each the other from to rise restraine;
And form'd so liuely in each perfect part
Might be maintaynd, and each gan diuersely deuize.
Now making girlonds of each flowre that grew,
She secretly would search each daintie lim,
And in each gentle hart desire of honour breeds.
And honour both; for each of other worthy are.
How like a Gyaunt in each manly part
Then each to other well affectionate,
And in each point her selfe informd aright,
Searching all lands and each remotest part,
And thy moyst mountaines each on others throng,
Themselues they did dispart, each to assay,
And of each turning still kept warie heed:
And sheweth each thing, as it is indeed:
And rubd his temples, and each trembling vaine;
So striuing each did other more augment,
And gazing each on other, nought bespake:
Vp they them tooke, each one a babe vptooke,
Franckly each paramour his leman knowes,
Each bird his mate, ne any does enuie
Each shade she saw, and each noyse she did heare,
Each shade she saw, and each noyse she did heare,
So both at her, and each at other wondered.
She went in perill, of each noyse affeard,
And of each shade, that did it selfe present;
May meet againe, and each take happie chance.
And so defide them each, and so defide them both.
That each awhile lay like a sencelesse corse.
And welcomed themselues. Each gan vndight
And each on other, and they all on her
And each did striue the other to out-goe,
Long were to tell each other louely fit,
To search each secret of that goodly sted,
But feard each shadow mouing to and fro,
But walkt each where, for feare of hid mischaunce,
Dying each day with inward wounds of dolours dart.
All three to each vnlike, yet all made in one mould.
Each other of loues bitter fruit despoile.
That each to other made, as oft befell.
Of this and that, according to each wit:
So diuersely each one did sundrie doubts deuise.
That each the other gan with passion great,
And dayly more offensiue vnto each degree.
That each of life sought others to depriue,
Do meete together, each abacke rebowndes
For her that each of you alike doth loth,
After each beautie, that appeard in sight,
Forgetfull each to haue bene euer others frend.
Each other horse and man to ground did send;
Like two mad mastiffes each on other flew,
So furiously each other did assayle,
Hath lately caus'd to be proclaim'd each where
Tho each to other did his faith engage,
And each not farre behinde him had his make,
These three did loue each other dearely well,
And to her seruice bind each liuing creature;
Then since (quoth she) the terme of each mans life
And loue each other deare, what euer them befell.
That made them dearely lou'd of each degree;
As if that each ment other to deuoure;
And each to other seemd the victorie to yield.
And fiercely each assayling, gan afresh to fight.
Instead of strokes, each other kissed glad,
The which as life were each to other liefe.
Sith each of them his Ladie had him by,
Whose beautie each of them thought excellent,
Chaufing and foming choler each against his fo.
Each labouring t'aduance the others gest,
And each of other gan inquire his name.
Appear'd in place, the which each other did outgoe.
To tell the feature of each goodly face.
And each one thought, as to their fancies came.
Each one profest to be her paramoure,
To whom each one his chalenge should disclame,
Then when she long had lookt vpon each one,
In which poursuit how each one did succeede,
And each did other much bewaile and mone;
That each of them from other sundred were,
And each vnto his lust did make a lawe,
Ne each of other feared fraud or tort,
So dreadfull strokes each did at other driue,
And each one taking part in others aide,
But sooth is said, and tride in each degree,
Though of contrarie natures each to other:
Which loue he red to be, that leads each liuing kind.
And each of either take his share aright.
They each at other tyrannously flew;
The maysterdome of each by force to gaine,
So ought each Knight, that vse of perill has,
Each one did flie; their hearts began to faile,
And all the sea, deuided each from either:
And looke what surplus did of each remaine,
And each estate quite out of order go'th?
Or else two falses, of each equall share;
As each one had his furnitures deuiz'd.
Both darting forth faire beames to each mans eye,
Vnder my foote let each lay downe his sword,
So each of them layd downe his sword out of his hand.
And each one had his right. Then Artegall
That to the Moone it mote be like in each respect.
Each hour did seeme a moneth, & euery moneth a yeare.
Each rowme she sought, but them all empty fond:
There present saw, each one of sence bereft,
Each of whose lockes did match a man in might,
And Ventailes reare, each other to behold.
Which he vnto her people does each day,
Who whenas each of other had a sight,
And tryde all waies, how each mote entrance make
To pay each with his owne is right and dew.
To all of each degree, as doth behoue?
As then the guize was for each gentle swayne;
Each others griefe with zeale affectionate,
And each sought to supply the office of her page.
This wize did they each other entertaine,
How each to entertaine with curt'sie well beseene,
But each the other vow'd t'accompany,
Betwixt them to diuide, and each to make his owne.
As he is wont at each Saint Valentide,
Of all her gifts, that pleasde each liuing sight,
Each gan his fellow solace and embrace,
As each thought best to spend the lingring space.
And of the pray each one a part doth beare.
Each wisheth to him selfe, and to the rest enuyes.
And each his sundrie sheepe with seuerall care
For they to each such fortune doe diffuse,
As they doe know each can most aptly vse.
With that they hold: each hath his fortune in his brest.
Sith each vnto himselfe his life may fortunize.
Since then in each mans self (said Calidore)
They teach vs, how to each degree and kynde
Doe fall together, stryuing each to get
And each to other calling, did compell
Looking each houre into deathes mouth to fall,
And rageth sore in each degree and state;
And of eachone he met, he tydings did inquere.
As when an eager mastiffe once doth proue
And with more eager felnesse him pursew'd:
Which as an Eagle, seeing pray appeare,
As Eagle fresh out of the Ocean waue,
Who trussing me, as Eagle doth his pray,
Like to an Eagle in his kingly pride,
And made to fly, like doues, whom the Eagle doth affray.
For one of them was like an Eagles claw,
As Eagles eye, that can behold the Sunne:
For as a Bittur in the Eagles claw,
Twise was he seene in soaring Eagles shape,
And Eagles wings, for scope and speedinesse,
Best musicke breeds delight in loathing eare:
Thus gan to say. But eare he thus had said,
O pardon, and vouchsafe with patient eare
The Palmer lent his eare vnto the noyce,
Came to the Ladies eare, which there did dwell,
Of all that mote delight a daintie eare,
For all that pleasing is to liuing eare,
But to her cry they list not lenden eare,
And lent her wary eare to vnderstand,
But standing high aloft, low lay thine eare,
Tydings hereof came to his mothers eare;
And Peece, that vnto parley eare will giue,
And in his eare him rounded close behind:
He whispered in her eare, and did her tell,
And sow vaine sorrow in a fruitlesse eare,
Ne let his speeches come vnto their eare.
To lend an eare, and softly to relent.
And drew thereto, making her eare her guide.
So she them seeing past the reach of eare,
Whereof when tydings came vnto mine eare,
Ne lend an eare to ought, that might behoue,
For heauen that vnto all lends equall eare,
The eare must be the ballance, to decree
Strange were the words in Britomartis eare;
By this came tydings to the Tyrants eare,
Of all that pleasant is to eare or eye,
Whylest thus he talkt, the knight with greedy eare
Where earely waite him many a gazing eye,
And made him pray both earely and eke late:
The trees did bud, and earely blossomes bore,
So earely ere the grosse Earthes gryesy shade
Earely the morrow next, before that day
And earely, ere the morrow did vpreare
And earely ere the dawning day appeard,
And earely calling forth both man and beast,
Earely, so soone as Titans beames forth brust
Till that the morning, bringing earely light
Then his dull eares, to heare what she did tell;
Sends to my doubtfull eares these speaches rare,
And piteous plaints she filleth his dull eares,
And with her gealous termes his open eares abused.
About her eares, when Vna her did marke
Did out of order stray about her daintie eares.
That they encombred all mens eares and eyes,
And greedy eares her weake hart from her bore:
With matchlesse eares deformed and distort,
And as her eares so eke her feet were odde,
And downe both sides two wide long eares did glow,
More great then th'eares of Elephants by Indus flood.
Which passing through the eares, would pierce the hart,
Flew first abroad, and all mens eares possest,
The eares and hearts of all that goodly crew,
Let then this plaint vnto his eares be borne,
And to his doome with listfull eares did both attend.
About her eares, does beat her brest, & forhead knockes.
Was like enchantment, that through both the eares,
To Calepine, whose eares those shrieches shrill
Your eies, your eares, your tongue, your talk restraine
But early rose, and ere that dawning light
The morrow next gan early to appeare,
But early ere the morrow next gan reare
The ioyous day gan early to appeare,
Whose early foe awaiting him beside
Early and late it rong, at euening and at prime.
Early before the Morne with cremosin ray,
When forth from virgin bowre she comes in th'early morne.
Bewrayed had the world with early light,
Early before the heauens fairest light
So early in the morrow next he went
The morrow next the Prince did early rize,
Als Vna earnd her traueill to renew.
And sayd; Now sure ye well haue earn'd your meed,
And euer as he rode, his hart did earne
Leaue roaring, when in rage he for reuenge did earne.
Which when I red, my heart did inly earne,
Then gan her heart to faint, and quake, and earne,
Doth them compell to worke, to earne their meat,
But what their hands could earne by twisting linnen twyne.
Which when those knights had heard, their harts gan earne,
Which when the Prince heard tell, his heart gan earne
And euer his faint hart much earned at the sight.
And crowned her twixt earnest and twixt game;
So can he turne his earnest vnto game,
Therewith she laught, and did her earnest end in iest.
And somewhat gan relent his earnest pace,
Vnto his reskew, and with earnest cry,
Came to that Castle, and with earnest mone,
For fire in earnest, ran with fearefull speed,
Sith late he fled from his too earnest foe:
Her earnest mind, yet wist not what it might intend.
And earnest search, where it was kept in store
How earnest suit she earst for him had made
And now for helpe aloud in earnest cride.
He gan his earnest feruour to augment,
Thereto they soone agreed, and earnest tooke,
But her of pardon prayd more earnestlie,
Did earnestly commit, and her coniure,
The thing, that thou didst craue so earnestly,
The warlike Mayde beholding earnestly
Yet he to them so earnestly did call,
And oft of them did earnestly inquire,
And earnestly besought, to wend that day
And earnestly entreated that they might
With which the armes, that earst so bright did show,
And quickning faith, that earst was woxen weake,
Euen he it was, that earst would haue supprest
But had he beene, where earst his armes were lent,
Can speake his prowesse, that did earst you beare,
Who earst in flowres of freshest youth was clad.
Isorrowed all so much, as earst I ioyd,
That earst vs held in loue of lingring life;
The man that would not liue, but earst lay at deathes dore.
Whom fyrie steele now burnt, that earst him arm'd,
She onely she it is, that earst did throw
Whom his victorious hands did earst restore
And fell intent ye did at earst me meet;
By other accident that earst befell,
For since the Redcrosse knight he earst did weet,
The ill, which earst to him, he now to Guyon ment.
Whose right haunch earst my stedfast arrow strake?
Sith earst into this forrest wild I came.
Which was the cause, when earst that horne I heard,
And furious fits at earst quite weren quaild:
What hellish furie hath at earst thee hent?
Where Mammon earst did sunne his threasury:
Who meeting earst with Archimago slie,
That he, wich earst them combatted, was Guyon bold.
And now the other, whom he earst did daunt,
Now one, which earst were many, made through variaunce.
All that did earst it hinder and molest,
That earst was sought to decke both bed and bowre,
With which she earst tryumphed, now did quail
Hee turnd againe, and chearefull looks as earst did shew.
By which the Redcrosse knight did earst display
Was earst impressed in her gentle spright:
To wreake the wrath, which he did earst reuiue
Of her rich spoyles, whom he had earst destroyd,
Much more then earst, and would haue algates riued
Who with Sir Satyrane, as earst ye red,
Which earst to you I playnd: for neither may
It often fals, (as here it earst befell)
The crime, which cursed Ate kindled earst,
And hauing me all wearie earst, downe feld,
Then all his former parts did earst appere.
It's now at earst become a stonie one;
And made them stoupe, that looked earst so hie.
The wretched mayd that earst desir'd to die,
How earnest suit she earst for him had made
From whom she earst so fast away did flie;
Of that proud Souldan, whom he earst did slay.
That earst was dead, restor'd to life againe,
Sir Artegall, albe he earst did wyte
By those, which earst did fly away for feare
Earst chawd thereon, yet was not all so dead,
Whereof she now more glad, then sory earst,
Him much more now, then earst he gan admire,
That this was he, whom Tristram earst did slay,
The gentle Aladine did earst inuade,
How great a hazard she at earst had made
Full loth am I (quoth he) as now at earst,
Which earst he left, he signes vnto them made,
That which your selfe haue earst ared so right?
So different from that, which earst ye seem'd in sight?
The which I earst aduentur'd for your sake.
Till I haue sau'd so many, as I earst did slay.
Of faire Serena, who as earst you heard,
Then Coridon woxe frollicke, that earst seemed dead.
On which he safety hopes, that earst feard to be lost.
And all such persons, as he earst did wrong,
Amid the bowels of the earth full steepe,
With bloudy mouth his mother earth did kis,
Let fall her eyen, as shamefast to the earth,
Where noblest knights were to be found on earth:
The earth shall sooner leaue her kindly skill
Looking to heauen; for earth she did disdayne,
And henceforth nothing faire, but her on earth they find.
And trample th'earth, the whiles they may respire;
That all the earth for terrour seemd to shake,
The greatest Earth his vncouth mother was,
The sad earth wounded with so sore assay,
And shooting in the earth, casts vp a mount of clay.
Out of the earth, with blade all burning bright
The stedfast globe of earth, as it for feare did quake.
And is the wisest now on earth I weene;
In heauen and earth? did not he all create
And her embracing said, O happie earth,
That was on earth not easie to compare;
Then come thou man of earth, and see the way,
Aboue all knights on earth, that batteill vndertake.
That with their horrour heauen and earth did ring,
As they the earth would shoulder from her seat,
From off the earth, with durty bloud distaynd,
That to the earth him droue, as stricken dead,
The face of earth, and wayes of liuing wight,
So downe he fell, that th'earth him vnderneath
Ne reard aboue the earth his flaming creast,
As on the earth, great mother of vs all,
Which medling with their bloud and earth, he threw
So shedding many teares, they closd the earth againe.
That ouer all the earth it may be seene;
But it were that, which noblest knight on earth doth weare.
From off the earth to take his aerie flight.
Into the hollow earth, them there to hide.
And in the hollow earth haue their eternall brood.
Which mortall Princes wore, whiles they on earth did rayne.
Not such, as earth out of her fruitfull woomb
On earth like neuer grew, ne liuing wight
Below the earth, might suffred be to stay:
And with her light the earth enlumines cleare;
Soone it must turne to earth; no earthly thing is sure.
Which though from earth it be deriued right,
And gaue against his mother earth a gronefull sownd.
From th'earth, & from her wombe new spirits to reprize.
How th'Earth his mother was, and first him bore;
For all that here on earth we dreadfull hold,
Of richest substaunce, that on earth might bee,
Nothing on earth mote alwaies happie beene.
Where now on earth, or how he may be found;
Betwixt the lowest earth and heauens hight,
Which through the earth haue spred their liuing prayse,
And quite from of th'earth their memory be rast?
That the fast earth affronted them so sore,
Now lyest thou a lumpe of earth forlorne,
The cold earth was his couch, the hard steele his pillow.
The bitter earth, and bad to let him in
Looking with myld aspect vpon the earth,
Where most she wonnes, whe[n] she on earth does dwel.
Through incest, her of his owne mother Earth
Whose like on earth was neuer framed yit,
Were ouerthrowne and layd on th'earth full cold,
Ne he twixt heauen and earth shall hide his hed,
Abiecting, th'earth with his faire forhead strooke:
Whiles thus on earth great Ioue these pageaunts playd,
